        "### 1. Fundamental Idea of Backpropagation\n",
        "\n",
        "Backpropagation is the cornerstone algorithm for training artificial neural networks. Its primary purpose is to efficiently compute the **gradient of the loss function with respect to the weights and biases** of the network. These gradients are essential because they tell us how much to adjust each weight and bias to reduce the loss, thereby improving the network's performance. This adjustment is typically performed by an optimization algorithm like Gradient Descent.\n",
        "\n",
        "The core idea behind backpropagation is the **repeated application of the chain rule** from calculus. It works by propagating the error (or gradient of the loss) backward through the network, starting from the output layer and moving towards the input layer. At each layer, it computes the gradient of the loss with respect to the local parameters (weights and biases) and also with respect to the activations of the previous layer. This allows for the efficient calculation of all necessary gradients without having to calculate each one independently, which would be computationally prohibitive for deep networks."
